ture, and how it ultimately became the language of rebellion against the system that produced it. Converting Words includes original analyses of the linguistic practices of both missionaries and Mayas-as found in bilingual dictionaries, grammars, catechisms, land documents, native chronicles, petitions, and the forbidden Maya Books of Chilam Balam. Lucidly written and vividly detailed, this important work presents a new approach to the study of religious and cultural conversion that will illuminate the history of Latin America and beyond, and will be essential reading across disciplinary boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 06880-02aMayasxReligion. 0aCatechisms, Spanish. 0aChristianity and culturexMexicoxYucatán (State). 0aChristianity and culturezMexicozYucatán (State) 0aChristianity and culturezMexicozYucatán (State). 0aChristianity and other religionsxMexicoxYucatán (State). 0aChristianity and other religionszMexicozYucatán (State) 0aChristianity and other religionszMexicozYucatán (State). 0aMaya languagexInfluence on SpanishxMexicoxYucatán (State). 0aMaya languagezMexicozYucatán (State)xInfluence on Spanish. 0aMaya languagezMexicozYucatán (State)xInfluence on Spanish. 0aMayasxColonization. 0aMayasxReligion. 0aSpanish languagexInfluence on MayaxMexicoxYucatán (State). 0aSpanish languagezMexicozYucatán (State)xInfluence on Maya. 0aSpanish languagezMexicozYucatán (State)xInfluence on Maya. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520944916.jpg